01:00:00,340 --> 01:00:02,060
Lovely. Now get back to work.

1047
01:00:02,060 --> 01:00:02,820
We open tonight.

1048
01:00:04,420 --> 01:00:06,580
- Doesn't it bother you? - What?

1049
01:00:06,580 --> 01:00:08,940
That the painting's a fake.

1050
01:00:08,940 --> 01:00:11,950
- What? - It's a fake. It has to be.

1051
01:00:11,950 --> 01:00:12,820
It's the only possible explanation.

1052
01:00:12,820 --> 01:00:15,870
You are in charge, aren't you, Miss Wenceslas?

1053
01:00:15,870 --> 01:00:16,380
Who are you?

1054
01:00:16,380 --> 01:00:18,460
Alex Woodbridge knew that the painting was a fake,

1055
01:00:18,460 --> 01:00:20,380
...so somebody sent the Golem to take care of him. Was it you?

1056
01:00:20,380 --> 01:00:22,340
Golem? What the hell are you talking about?

1057
01:00:22,340 --> 01:00:25,100
Are you working for someone else? Did you fake it for them?

1058
01:00:25,100 --> 01:00:26,580
It's not a fake.

1059
01:00:26,580 --> 01:00:28,380
It is a fake. I don't know why.

1060
01:00:28,380 --> 01:00:30,660
But there's something wrong with it, there has to be.

1061
01:00:30,660 --> 01:00:32,060
What the hell are you on about?

1062
01:00:32,060 --> 01:00:34,700
- You know I could have you sacked on the spot. - Not a problem.

1063
01:00:34,700 --> 01:00:36,500
- No? - No, I don't work here, you see.

1064
01:00:36,500 --> 01:00:38,780
Just popped in to give you a bit of friendly advice.

1065
01:00:38,780 --> 01:00:40,500
How did you get in?

1066
01:00:40,500 --> 01:00:42,700
- Please! - I want to know.

1067
01:00:42,700 --> 01:00:46,020
The art of disguise is knowing how to hide in plain sight.

1068
01:00:46,020 --> 01:00:47,900
- Who are you? - Sherlock Holmes.

1069
01:00:47,900 --> 01:00:50,340
Am I supposed to be impressed?

1070
01:00:50,340 --> 01:00:52,580
You should be.

1071
01:00:52,580 --> 01:00:54,140
Have a nice day.

1072
01:01:10,140 --> 01:01:13,540
He wouldn't. He just wouldn't.

1073
01:01:13,540 --> 01:01:16,310
Strange things have happened.

1074
01:01:16,310 --> 01:01:18,860
Westie wasn't a traitor.

1075
01:01:18,860 --> 01:01:20,620
That's a horrible thing to say!

1076
01:01:20,620 --> 01:01:23,460
I'm sorry. But you must understand...

1077
01:01:23,460 --> 01:01:26,140
That's what they think, isn't it, his bosses?

1078
01:01:26,140 --> 01:01:28,210
He was young man, about to get married,

1079
01:01:28,210 --> 01:01:28,710
...he had debts.

1080
01:01:28,710 --> 01:01:31,460
Everyone's got debts,

1081
01:01:31,460 --> 01:01:34,860
and Westie wouldn't want to clear them by selling out his country.

1082
01:01:34,860 --> 01:01:39,860
Can you, er...? Can you tell me exactly what happened that night?

1083
01:01:40,100 --> 01:01:43,220
We were having a night in.

1084
01:01:43,220 --> 01:01:46,220
Just...watching a DVD.

1085
01:01:46,220 --> 01:01:49,660
He normally falls asleep, you know, but he sat through this one.

1086
01:01:51,460 --> 01:01:53,060
He was quiet.

1087
01:01:55,140 --> 01:01:58,780
Out of the blue he said he just had to go and see someone.

1088
01:01:58,780 --> 01:02:00,020
And you've no idea who?

1089
01:02:07,820 --> 01:02:10,460
Hi, Liz. You OK, love?

1090
01:02:10,460 --> 01:02:12,620
- Yeah. - Who's this?

1091
01:02:12,620 --> 01:02:16,260
- John Watson, hi. - This is my brother, Joe.

1092
01:02:16,260 --> 01:02:18,500
John's trying to find out what happened to Westie, Joe.

1093
01:02:18,500 --> 01:02:20,780
- You with the police? - Sort of, yeah.

1094
01:02:20,780 --> 01:02:23,740
Tell them to get off their arses, will you? It's bloody ridiculous.

1095
01:02:23,740 --> 01:02:25,220
I'll do my best.

1096
01:02:32,460 --> 01:02:37,300
Thanks very much for your help. Again, I'm very, very sorry.

1097
01:02:37,300 --> 01:02:39,860
He didn't steal those things, Mr Watson.

1098
01:02:41,020 --> 01:02:44,260
I knew Westie, he was a good man.

1099
01:02:44,260 --> 01:02:46,740
He was my good man.

1100
01:03:09,900 --> 01:03:11,900
- Spare change? - No.

1101
01:03:11,900 --> 01:03:14,300
Any spare change?

1102
01:03:20,940 --> 01:03:23,660
Alex Woodbridge didn't know anything special about art.

1103
01:03:23,660 --> 01:03:25,300
- And? - And...

1104
01:03:25,300 --> 01:03:25,890
Is that it?

1105
01:03:25,890 --> 01:03:27,860
No habits, hobbies, personality?

1106
01:03:27,860 --> 01:03:30,140
Give us a chance. He was an amateur astronomer.

1107
01:03:30,140 --> 01:03:31,760
Hold that cab.

1108
01:03:31,760 --> 01:03:32,890
Spare change, sir?

1109
01:03:32,890 --> 01:03:33,580
Don't mind if I do.

1110
01:03:33,580 --> 01:03:35,300
Can you wait here?

1111
01:03:35,300 --> 01:03:38,550


1112
01:03:38,300 --> 01:03:42,820
Fortunately, I haven't been idle. Come on.

1113
01:04:05,740 --> 01:04:07,420
Beautiful, isn't it?

1114
01:04:10,380 --> 01:04:11,950
I thought you didn't care about...

1115
01:04:11,950 --> 01:04:15,060
Doesn't mean I can't appreciate it.

1116
01:04:15,060 --> 01:04:18,860
Listen, Alex Woodbridge had a message on the answerphone at his flat.

1117
01:04:18,860 --> 01:04:20,860
- A Professor Cairns. - This way.

1118
01:04:21,900 --> 01:04:25,220
Nice. Nice part of town.

1119
01:04:28,260 --> 01:04:30,430
Any time you want to explain?

1120
01:04:30,430 --> 01:04:31,380
Homeless network.

1121
01:04:31,380 --> 01:04:34,500
- Really is indispensable. - Homeless network?

1122
01:04:34,500 --> 01:04:36,760
My eyes and ears, all over the city.

1123
01:04:36,760 --> 01:04:37,900
Ah, that's...clever.

1124
01:04:37,900 --> 01:04:40,100
So you scratch their backs, and...?

1125
01:04:40,100 --> 01:04:41,900
Yes, then disinfect myself.

1126
01:05:00,980 --> 01:05:02,580
Sherlock! Come on!

1127
01:05:03,200 --> 01:05:05,200


1128
01:05:05,540 --> 01:05:07,580
What's he doing sleeping rough?

1129
01:05:07,580 --> 01:05:08,730
Well, he has a very distinctive look.

1130
01:05:08,730 --> 01:05:12,300
He has to hide somewhere where tongues won't wag...much.

1131
01:05:12,400 --> 01:05:13,460
- Oh, shit!  - What?

1132
01:05:13,460 --> 01:05:15,620
- I wish I... - Don't mention it.

1133
01:05:23,860 --> 01:05:26,130
No! No! No! No!

1134
01:05:26,850 --> 01:05:30,220
It'll take us weeks to find him again.

1135
01:05:30,220 --> 01:05:32,900
Or not. I have an idea where he might be going.

1136
01:05:32,900 --> 01:05:36,220
- What? - I told you, someone left Alex Woodbridge a message.

1137
01:05:36,220 --> 01:05:39,700
There can't be that many Professor Cairns in the book. Come on.

1138
01:05:45,900 --> 01:05:50,500
'Jupiter, the fifth planet in our solar system, and the largest.

1139
01:05:50,500 --> 01:05:53,520
'Jupiter is a gas giant.

1140
01:05:53,520 --> 01:05:55,900
Planet Earth would fit into it 11 times.'

1141
01:05:55,900 --> 01:05:57,980
Yes, we know that.

1142
01:06:02,060 --> 01:06:05,860
- 'Titan is the largest moon...' - Come on, Neptune.

1143
01:06:10,420 --> 01:06:13,060
'Many are actually long dead...'

1144
01:06:13,060 --> 01:06:16,060
- Tom, is that you? - '..exploded into supernovas.'

1145
01:06:18,220 --> 01:06:21,820
'Discovered by Urbain Le Verrier in 1846...'

1146
01:06:25,380 --> 01:06:28,780
'..composed mainly of hydrogen.'

1147
01:06:28,780 --> 01:06:31,860
- 'Their light takes so long to reach us...' - Golem!

1148
01:06:31,860 --> 01:06:36,260
'..many are actually long dead, exploded into...'

1149
01:06:37,980 --> 01:06:39,700
- I can't see him. - I'll go round.

1150
01:06:42,420 --> 01:06:44,500
Who are you working for this time, Dzundza?

1151
01:06:48,700 --> 01:06:52,740
'A star begins as a collapsing ball of material composed mainly of...'

1152
01:06:52,740 --> 01:06:54,860
Golem!

1153
01:06:57,700 --> 01:06:59,780
Let him go...

1154
01:06:59,780 --> 01:07:02,180
or I will kill you.

1155
01:07:10,300 --> 01:07:15,700
'The fourth planet of the solar system, named after the Roman god of war.'

1156
01:07:23,140 --> 01:07:26,340
'..it is a gas giant...'

1157
01:07:35,620 --> 01:07:38,060
'..takes so long to reach us...

1158
01:07:40,500 --> 01:07:42,700
'..into supernovas...'

1159
01:07:46,180 --> 01:07:49,380
'..exploded into supernovas...'

1160
01:07:51,220 --> 01:07:52,620
It's a fake. It has to be.

1161
01:07:52,620 --> 01:07:56,100
That painting has been subjected to every test known to science.

1162
01:07:54,460 --> 01:07:55,740


1163
01:07:53,980 --> 01:07:55,340


1164
01:07:54,140 --> 01:07:55,900


1165
01:07:56,100 --> 01:07:57,620
It's a very good fake, then.

1166
01:07:55,620 --> 01:07:57,020


1167
01:07:56,180 --> 01:07:56,980


1168
01:07:56,420 --> 01:07:57,380


1169
01:07:57,620 --> 01:07:58,650
You know about this, don't you?

1170
01:07:58,710 --> 01:08:00,580
This is you, isn't it?

1171
01:08:00,580 --> 01:08:02,220
Inspector, my time is being wasted.

1172
01:08:02,220 --> 01:08:05,460
Would you mind showing yourself and your friends out?

1173
01:08:06,660 --> 01:08:07,980
The painting is a fake.

1174
01:08:09,940 --> 01:08:13,740
It's a fake, that's why Woodbridge and Cairns were killed.

1175
01:08:15,300 --> 01:08:18,900
Oh, come on, proving is just a detail. The painting is a fake.

1176
01:08:18,900 --> 01:08:20,900
I've solved it, I've figured it out.

1177
01:08:20,900 --> 01:08:24,860
It's a fake, that's the answer, that's why they were killed.

1178
01:08:28,780 --> 01:08:31,490
OK, I'll prove it. Give me time.

1179
01:08:31,490 --> 01:08:32,100
Will you give me time?

1180
01:08:33,270 --> 01:08:34,640
 10...
'Ten...'

1181
01:08:34,640 --> 01:08:35,780
It's a kid.

1182
01:08:36,260 --> 01:08:37,250
Oh God, it's a kid.

1183
01:08:37,250 --> 01:08:38,620
- What did he say? - "Ten."

1184
01:08:38,620 --> 01:08:40,820
- 'Nine...' - It's a countdown. He's giving me time.

1185
01:08:40,820 --> 01:08:43,380
- Jesus... - It's a fake, but how can I prove it? How?! How?!

1186
01:08:43,380 --> 01:08:44,580
 8...
'Eight...'

1187
01:08:44,580 --> 01:08:45,730
This kid will die.

1188
01:08:45,730 --> 01:08:47,620
Tell me why the painting is a fake. Tell me!

1189
01:08:47,620 --> 01:08:48,740
- 'Seven...' - No, shut up.

1190
01:08:48,740 --> 01:08:50,940
Don't say anything. It only works if I figure it out.

1191
01:08:52,820 --> 01:08:55,380
It must be possible. It must be staring me in the face.

1192
01:08:55,380 --> 01:08:56,820
- 'Six...' - How?

1193
01:08:57,980 --> 01:09:00,180
- Woodbridge knew, but how?! - 'Five...'

1194
01:09:00,180 --> 01:09:02,020
It's speeding up! Sherlock!

1195
01:09:03,060 --> 01:09:05,300
- 'Four... - 'Oh! In the Planetarium, you heard it too.

1196
01:09:05,300 --> 01:09:07,340
Oh, that is brilliant, that is gorgeous!

1197
01:09:07,340 --> 01:09:09,620
- 'Three...' - What's brilliant? What is?!

1198
01:09:09,620 --> 01:09:10,810
This is beautiful.

1199
01:09:09,620 --> 01:09:10,810


1200
01:09:09,620 --> 01:09:10,810


1201
01:09:10,810 --> 01:09:11,660
Love this!

1202
01:09:11,660 --> 01:09:13,460
- 'Two...' - Sherlock!

1203
01:09:13,460 --> 01:09:15,780
The Van Buren Supernova.

1204
01:09:17,380 --> 01:09:21,020
'Please, is somebody there? Somebody help me.'

1205
01:09:21,020 --> 01:09:22,120
There you go.

1206
01:09:22,120 --> 01:09:25,420
Go and find out where he is and pick him up.

1207
01:09:25,420 --> 01:09:30,180
Van Buren Supernova, so-called.

1208
01:09:30,180 --> 01:09:34,340
Exploding star. Only appeared in the sky in 1858.

1209
01:09:34,340 --> 01:09:37,420
So how could it have been...

1210
01:09:37,420 --> 01:09:41,420
painted in the 1640s?

1211
01:09:45,100 --> 01:09:46,620


1212
01:09:46,620 --> 01:09:49,020
Oh, Sherl...

1213
01:09:52,420 --> 01:09:55,500
You know, it's interesting. Bohemian stationery,

1214
01:09:55,500 --> 01:09:59,980
an assassin named after a Prague legend, and you, Miss Wenceslas.

1215
01:09:59,980 --> 01:10:03,060
This whole case has a distinctly Czech feeling about it.

1216
01:10:03,060 --> 01:10:04,500
Is that where this leads?

1217
01:10:06,300 --> 01:10:09,260
What are we looking at, Inspector?

1218
01:10:09,260 --> 01:10:12,420
Well, criminal conspiracy, fraud,

1219
01:10:12,480 --> 01:10:15,260
accessory after the fact, at the very least.

1220
01:10:15,260 --> 01:10:17,660
The murder of the old woman, all the people in the flat...

1221
01:10:17,660 --> 01:10:20,060
I didn't know anything about that.

1222
01:10:20,060 --> 01:10:22,700
All those things, please, believe me.

1223
01:10:24,740 --> 01:10:27,500
I just wanted my share.

1224
01:10:27,500 --> 01:10:29,020
The 30 million.

1225
01:10:37,620 --> 01:10:39,780
I found a little old man in Argentina.

1226
01:10:41,660 --> 01:10:44,660
A genius - I mean, really.

1227
01:10:44,660 --> 01:10:46,620
Brushwork, immaculate.

1228
01:10:46,620 --> 01:10:50,220
Could fool anyone. Mmm.

1229
01:10:50,220 --> 01:10:51,740
Well, nearly anyone.

1230
01:10:54,900 --> 01:10:58,900
But I didn't know how to go about convincing the world the picture was genuine.

1231
01:11:00,380 --> 01:11:02,220
It was just an idea.

1232
01:11:03,820 --> 01:11:06,460
A spark which he blew into a flame.

1233
01:11:06,460 --> 01:11:08,180
Who?

1234
01:11:08,180 --> 01:11:09,780
I don't know.

1235
01:11:09,780 --> 01:11:12,340
It's true!

1236
01:11:12,340 --> 01:11:16,020
It took a long time, but eventually I was...

1237
01:11:16,020 --> 01:11:17,820
put in touch with people.

1238
01:11:20,220 --> 01:11:22,460
His people...

1239
01:11:23,740 --> 01:11:26,260
Well, there was never any real contact.

1240
01:11:28,100 --> 01:11:31,140
Just messages...

1241
01:11:33,140 --> 01:11:36,260
..whispers.

1242
01:11:36,260 --> 01:11:39,500
And did those whispers have a name?

1243
01:11:48,740 --> 01:11:50,500
Moriarty.

1244
01:12:05,780 --> 01:12:08,460
- So this is where West was found? - Yeah.

1245
01:12:08,460 --> 01:12:10,820
- Are you going to be long? - I might be.

1246
01:12:10,820 --> 01:12:12,060
- Are you the police, then? - Sort of.

1247
01:12:12,150 --> 01:12:14,660
- I hate 'em. - The police?

1248
01:12:14,660 --> 01:12:16,260
No, jumpers.

1249
01:12:16,260 --> 01:12:19,980
People who chuck 'emselves in front of trains. Selfish bastards.

1250
01:12:19,980 --> 01:12:22,780
Well, that's one way of looking at it.

1251
01:12:22,780 --> 01:12:25,260
I mean it. It's all right for them.

1252
01:12:25,260 --> 01:12:28,300
It's over in a split second, strawberry jam all over the lines.

1253
01:12:28,300 --> 01:12:29,220
What about the drivers, eh?

1254
01:12:29,220 --> 01:12:31,380
They've got to live with it, haven't they?

1255
01:12:31,380 --> 01:12:35,380
Yeah, speaking of strawberry jam, there's no blood on the line.

1256
01:12:35,380 --> 01:12:37,010
Has it been cleaned off?

1257
01:12:37,010 --> 01:12:39,060
No, there wasn't that much.

1258
01:12:39,060 --> 01:12:40,870
You said his head was smashed in.

1259
01:12:40,870 --> 01:12:42,540
It was, but there wasn't much blood.

1260
01:12:44,460 --> 01:12:46,360
OK.

1261
01:12:47,900 --> 01:12:50,180
Well, I'll leave you to it, then.

1262
01:12:50,180 --> 01:12:53,540
- Just give us a shout when you're off. - Right.

1263
01:12:53,540 --> 01:12:56,240
Right, so, Andrew West...

1264
01:12:56,520 --> 01:13:01,380
got on the train somewhere. Or did he?

1265
01:13:01,380 --> 01:13:04,020
There was no ticket on the body.

1266
01:13:05,580 --> 01:13:07,460
How did he end up here?

1267
01:13:14,260 --> 01:13:16,420
- The points. - Yes!

1268
01:13:16,420 --> 01:13:17,830
I knew you'd get there eventually.

1269
01:13:18,240 --> 01:13:20,230
West wasn't killed here,

1270
01:13:20,230 --> 01:13:21,300
that's why there was so little blood.

1271
01:13:21,300 --> 01:13:23,540
- How long have you been following me? - Since the start.

1272
01:13:23,540 --> 01:13:26,460
You don't think I'd give up on a case like this

1273
01:13:26,460 --> 01:13:28,340
just to spite my brother, do you?

1274
01:13:28,340 --> 01:13:31,740
Come on, we've got a bit of burglary to do.

1275
01:13:36,060 --> 01:13:38,140
Missile defence plans haven't left the country,

1276
01:13:38,140 --> 01:13:40,780
otherwise Mycroft's people would have heard about it.

1277
01:13:40,780 --> 01:13:44,060
Despite what people think, we do still have a secret service.

1278
01:13:44,060 --> 01:13:46,300
Yeah, I know, I've met them.

1279
01:13:46,300 --> 01:13:48,320
Which means whoever stole the memory stick

1280
01:13:48,320 --> 01:13:50,460
can't sell it or doesn't know what to do with it.

1281
01:13:50,460 --> 01:13:52,340
My money's on the latter.

1282
01:13:52,340 --> 01:13:53,940
We're here.

1283
01:13:53,940 --> 01:13:55,580
Where?

1284
01:14:04,380 --> 01:14:07,660
Sherlock! What if there's someone in?

1285
01:14:09,180 --> 01:14:11,380
There isn't.

1286
01:14:14,180 --> 01:14:15,380
Jesus...

1287
01:14:16,820 --> 01:14:17,560
Where are we?

1288
01:14:17,560 --> 01:14:20,220
Oh, sorry, didn't I say? Joe Harrison's flat.

1289
01:14:20,220 --> 01:14:21,700
Joe...?

1290
01:14:24,100 --> 01:14:27,860
Brother of West's fiancee. He stole the memory stick,

1291
01:14:27,860 --> 01:14:30,180
killed his prospective brother-in-law.

1292
01:14:43,140 --> 01:14:45,260
Then why did he do it?

1293
01:14:47,220 --> 01:14:48,740
Let's ask him.

1294
01:14:59,020 --> 01:15:00,460
Don't! Don't.

1295
01:15:05,580 --> 01:15:08,700
Wasn't meant to...

1296
01:15:11,220 --> 01:15:14,460
What's Lucy gonna say? Jesus.

1297
01:15:14,460 --> 01:15:15,740
Why did you kill him?

1298
01:15:15,740 --> 01:15:18,940
It was an accident. I swear it was.

1299
01:15:18,940 --> 01:15:23,860
But stealing the plans for the missile defence program wasn't an accident, was it?

1300
01:15:23,860 --> 01:15:26,020
I started dealing drugs.

1301
01:15:27,620 --> 01:15:29,940
I mean, the bike thing's a great cover, right?

1302
01:15:29,940 --> 01:15:34,940
I don't know how it started. I just got out of my depth.

1303
01:15:34,940 --> 01:15:39,380
I owed people thousands. Serious people.

1304
01:15:39,380 --> 01:15:44,020
Then at Westie's engagement do, he starts talking about his job.

1305
01:15:46,500 --> 01:15:49,100
I mean, usually, he's so careful.

1306
01:15:49,100 --> 01:15:53,980
'But that night, after a few pints, he really opened up.

1307
01:15:53,980 --> 01:15:56,260
'He told me about these missile plans.

1308
01:15:56,260 --> 01:15:58,940
'Beyond top secret.

1309
01:15:58,940 --> 01:16:02,820
He showed me the memory stick, he waved it in front of me.

1310
01:16:02,820 --> 01:16:05,580
You hear about these things getting lost,

1311
01:16:05,580 --> 01:16:07,620
ending up on rubbish tips and whatnot.

1312
01:16:07,620 --> 01:16:10,940
But there it was. And I thought...

1313
01:16:10,940 --> 01:16:13,980
'Well, I thought it could be worth a fortune.

1314
01:16:13,980 --> 01:16:17,020
It was pretty easy to get the thing off him, he was so plastered.'

1315
01:16:19,620 --> 01:16:21,900
Next time I saw him,

1316
01:16:21,900 --> 01:16:25,180
I could tell by the look on his face that he knew.

1317
01:16:25,180 --> 01:16:29,180
- What are you doing here? - What have you done with the plans?

1318
01:16:29,180 --> 01:16:31,780
What happened?

1319
01:16:37,020 --> 01:16:41,020
I was going to call an ambulance, but it was too late.

1320
01:16:41,020 --> 01:16:46,420
I just didn't have a clue what to do. So I dragged him in 'ere.'

1321
01:16:46,420 --> 01:16:49,700
I just sat in the dark, thinking.

1322
01:16:50,700 --> 01:16:53,140
When a neat little idea popped into your head.

1323
01:17:33,620 --> 01:17:36,500
Carrying Andrew West way away from here.

1324
01:17:36,500 --> 01:17:38,380
His body would have gone on for ages

1325
01:17:38,380 --> 01:17:41,460
if the train hadn't hit a stretch of track that curved.

1326
01:17:41,460 --> 01:17:43,580
- And points. - Exactly.

1327
01:17:46,980 --> 01:17:49,820
Do you still have it, then - the memory stick?

1328
01:17:51,340 --> 01:17:54,340
Fetch it for me, if you wouldn't mind.

1329
01:18:03,780 --> 01:18:05,900
Distraction over - the game continues.

1330
01:18:05,900 --> 01:18:08,540
Maybe that's over, too. We've heard nothing from the bomber.

1331
01:18:08,540 --> 01:18:09,980
Five pips, remember, John.

1332
01:18:09,980 --> 01:18:13,820
It's a countdown. We've only had four.

1333
01:18:17,380 --> 01:18:22,020
No, no, no! Course he's not the boy's father.

1334
01:18:22,020 --> 01:18:24,220
Look at the turn-ups on his jeans!

1335
01:18:25,820 --> 01:18:30,700
I knew it was dangerous. Getting you into crap telly.

1336
01:18:30,700 --> 01:18:33,500
Not a patch on Connie Prince.

1337
01:18:33,500 --> 01:18:35,980
Have you given Mycroft the memory stick yet?

1338
01:18:35,980 --> 01:18:37,900
Yep. He was over the moon.

1339
01:18:37,900 --> 01:18:41,740
Threatened me with a knighthood...again.

1340
01:18:42,420 --> 01:18:45,500
- You know, I'm still waiting. - Hm?

1341
01:18:45,500 --> 01:18:48,460
For you to admit that a little knowledge of the solar system

1342
01:18:48,460 --> 01:18:51,060
and you'd have cleared up the fake painting a lot quicker.

1343
01:18:51,060 --> 01:18:52,660
It didn't do you any good, did it?

1344
01:18:52,660 --> 01:18:55,220
No, but I'm not the world's only consulting detective.

1345
01:18:55,220 --> 01:18:56,900
- True. - I won't be in for tea.

1346
01:18:56,900 --> 01:19:01,020
I'm going to Sarah's. There's still some of that risotto left in the fridge.

1347
01:19:01,020 --> 01:19:03,620
- Milk, we need milk. - I'll get some.

1348
01:19:03,620 --> 01:19:05,380
- Really? - Really.

1349
01:19:07,620 --> 01:19:10,260
- And some beans, then? - Mm.

1350
01:19:31,260 --> 01:19:34,260


1351
01:19:38,660 --> 01:19:43,260


1352
01:20:23,340 --> 01:20:27,340
Bought you a little getting-to-know-you present.

1353
01:20:27,340 --> 01:20:29,900
That's what it's all been for, isn't it?

1354
01:20:32,540 --> 01:20:34,820
All your little puzzles, making me dance.

1355
01:20:34,820 --> 01:20:38,220
All to distract me from this.

1356
01:20:50,340 --> 01:20:51,820
Evening.

1357
01:20:56,940 --> 01:20:59,380
This is a turn-up, isn't it, Sherlock?

1358
01:20:59,380 --> 01:21:01,550
John! What the hell...?

1359
01:21:01,560 --> 01:21:03,540
Bet you never saw this coming.

1360
01:21:10,340 --> 01:21:16,980
What...would you like me to make him say...next?

1361
01:21:18,780 --> 01:21:23,900
- Gottle o' gear, gottle o' gear, gottle o' gear. - Stop it.

1362
01:21:23,900 --> 01:21:27,180
Nice touch, this. The pool,

1363
01:21:27,180 --> 01:21:29,700
where little Carl died.

1364
01:21:29,700 --> 01:21:35,420
I stopped him. I can stop John Watson, too.

1365
01:21:35,420 --> 01:21:40,300
- Stop his heart. - Who are you?

1366
01:21:41,740 --> 01:21:44,460
I gave you my number.

1367
01:21:44,460 --> 01:21:47,060
I thought you might call.

1368
01:22:01,300 --> 01:22:04,700
Is that a British Army Browning L9A1 in your pocket,

1369
01:22:04,700 --> 01:22:08,220
or are you just pleased to see me?

1370
01:22:09,260 --> 01:22:10,540
Both.

1371
01:22:12,620 --> 01:22:16,100
Jim Moriarty. Hi.

1372
01:22:18,340 --> 01:22:20,500
Jim?

1373
01:22:20,500 --> 01:22:22,620
Jim from the hospital?

1374
01:22:25,020 --> 01:22:27,780
Oh, did I really make such a fleeting impression?

1375
01:22:27,780 --> 01:22:31,140
But then, I suppose, that was rather the point.

1376
01:22:33,020 --> 01:22:37,420
Don't be silly. Someone else is holding the rifle.

1377
01:22:37,420 --> 01:22:39,460
I don't like getting my hands dirty.

1378
01:22:42,940 --> 01:22:46,240
I've given you a glimpse, Sherlock,

1379
01:22:46,240 --> 01:22:48,020
just a teensy glimpse

1380
01:22:48,020 --> 01:22:52,700
of what I've got going on out there in the big bad world.

1381
01:22:52,700 --> 01:22:56,100
I'm a specialist, you see.

1382
01:22:56,100 --> 01:22:57,740
Like you.

1383
01:22:57,740 --> 01:22:59,220
Dear Jim...

1384
01:23:01,060 --> 01:23:04,460
..please will you fix it for me

1385
01:23:04,460 --> 01:23:07,740
to get rid of my lover's nasty sister?

1386
01:23:07,740 --> 01:23:10,390
Dear Jim, please will you fix it for me

1387
01:23:10,390 --> 01:23:11,580
to disappear to South America?

1388
01:23:11,580 --> 01:23:13,180
Just so.

1389
01:23:13,180 --> 01:23:16,260
Consulting criminal.

1390
01:23:16,260 --> 01:23:20,100
- Brilliant. - Isn't it?

1391
01:23:20,100 --> 01:23:23,020
No-one ever gets to me.

1392
01:23:24,860 --> 01:23:26,500
And no-one ever will.

1393
01:23:26,500 --> 01:23:27,700
I did.

1394
01:23:27,700 --> 01:23:30,020
You've come the closest. Now you're in my way.

1395
01:23:30,020 --> 01:23:31,860
- Thank you. - Didn't mean it as a compliment.

1396
01:23:31,860 --> 01:23:34,020
- Yes, you did. - Yeah, OK, I did.

1397
01:23:34,020 --> 01:23:35,780
But the flirting's over, Sherlock.

1398
01:23:35,780 --> 01:23:38,740
Daddy's had enough now.

1399
01:23:38,740 --> 01:23:41,220
I've shown you what I can do.

1400
01:23:41,220 --> 01:23:45,140
I cut loose all those people, all those little problems,

1401
01:23:45,140 --> 01:23:47,020
even 30 million quid,

1402
01:23:47,020 --> 01:23:48,900
just to get you to come out and play.

1403
01:23:48,900 --> 01:23:53,060
So take this as a friendly warning... my dear.

1404
01:23:53,060 --> 01:23:55,780
Back off.

1405
01:23:57,460 --> 01:24:01,100
Although I have loved this,

1406
01:24:01,100 --> 01:24:03,020
this little game of ours.

1407
01:24:03,020 --> 01:24:06,490
Playing Jim from IT. Playing gay.

1408
01:24:06,490 --> 01:24:08,660
Did you like the little touch with the underwear?

1409
01:24:08,660 --> 01:24:11,460
- People have died. - That's what people do!

1410
01:24:14,220 --> 01:24:17,300
- I will stop you. - No, you won't.

1411
01:24:17,300 --> 01:24:18,660
Are you all right?

1412
01:24:20,820 --> 01:24:22,820
You can talk, Johnny boy.

1413
01:24:22,820 --> 01:24:25,220
Go ahead.

1414
01:24:25,220 --> 01:24:28,940
- Take it. - Mm? .

1415
01:24:30,060 --> 01:24:33,300
Oh...that? The missile plans.

1416
01:24:37,660 --> 01:24:38,900
Boring!

1417
01:24:38,900 --> 01:24:41,940
I could've got them anyway.

1418
01:24:41,940 --> 01:24:44,340
Sherlock, run!

1419
01:24:44,340 --> 01:24:46,860
Good!

1420
01:24:46,860 --> 01:24:50,140
Very good.

1421
01:24:50,140 --> 01:24:52,840
If your sniper pulls that trigger, Mr Moriarty,

1422
01:24:52,840 --> 01:24:54,340
then we both go up.

1423
01:24:54,340 --> 01:24:55,550
Isn't he sweet?

1424
01:24:55,550 --> 01:24:57,820
I can see why you like having him around.

1425
01:24:57,820 --> 01:25:00,740
But then, people do get so sentimental about their pets.

1426
01:25:00,740 --> 01:25:02,660
They're so touchingly loyal.

1427
01:25:02,660 --> 01:25:03,900
But oops!

1428
01:25:05,140 --> 01:25:08,700
You've rather shown your hand there, Dr Watson.

1429
01:25:13,140 --> 01:25:14,580
Gotcha.

1430
01:25:19,180 --> 01:25:21,370
Westwood.

1431
01:25:21,370 --> 01:25:23,310
Do you know what happens if you don't leave me alone,

1432
01:25:23,320 --> 01:25:24,780
Sherlock? To you?

1433
01:25:24,780 --> 01:25:27,620
Oh, let me guess. I get killed.

1434
01:25:27,620 --> 01:25:29,140
Kill you?

1435
01:25:29,140 --> 01:25:31,090
No, don't be obvious.

1436
01:25:31,090 --> 01:25:33,540
I mean, I'm going to kill you anyway, some day.

1437
01:25:33,540 --> 01:25:35,420
I don't want to rush it, though.

1438
01:25:35,420 --> 01:25:37,620
I am saving it up for something special.

1439
01:25:37,620 --> 01:25:41,620
No, no, no, no, no. If you don't stop prying,

1440
01:25:41,620 --> 01:25:43,620
I'll burn you.

1441
01:25:46,180 --> 01:25:50,620
I'll burn the heart out of you.

1442
01:25:51,900 --> 01:25:55,380
I have been reliably informed that I don't have one.

1443
01:25:55,380 --> 01:25:57,380
But we both know that's not quite true.

1444
01:26:01,260 --> 01:26:04,660
Well, I'd better be off.

1445
01:26:04,660 --> 01:26:07,940
Well, so nice to have had a proper chat.

1446
01:26:07,940 --> 01:26:09,780
What if I was to shoot you now?

1447
01:26:09,780 --> 01:26:12,100
Right now?

1448
01:26:12,100 --> 01:26:15,380
Then you could cherish the look of surprise on my face.

1449
01:26:16,420 --> 01:26:18,180
Cos I'd be surprised, Sherlock.

1450
01:26:18,180 --> 01:26:19,900
Really, I would.

1451
01:26:19,900 --> 01:26:24,540
And just a teensy bit...disappointed.

1452
01:26:27,020 --> 01:26:29,660
And of course, you wouldn't be able to cherish it for very long.

1453
01:26:31,220 --> 01:26:34,700
Ciao, Sherlock Holmes.

1454
01:26:36,220 --> 01:26:40,980
Catch you...later.

1455
01:26:42,140 --> 01:26:44,940
No, you won't!

1456
01:26:50,380 --> 01:26:52,780
All right? Are you all right?

1457
01:26:52,780 --> 01:26:56,940
Yeah, I'm fine. I'm fine. Sherlock...

1458
01:26:56,940 --> 01:26:58,780
Sherlock!

1459
01:27:05,540 --> 01:27:06,980
Oh, Christ.

1460
01:27:16,860 --> 01:27:20,980
- Are you OK? - Me? Yeah, fine. I'm fine. Fine.

1461
01:27:23,420 --> 01:27:27,420
That, er...thing that you...that you did,

1462
01:27:27,420 --> 01:27:32,940
that, um...you offered to do...that was, um...good.

1463
01:27:34,420 --> 01:27:38,420
- I'm glad no-one saw that. - Mm?

1464
01:27:38,420 --> 01:27:41,500
You ripping my clothes off in a darkened swimming pool.

1465
01:27:41,500 --> 01:27:42,580
People might talk.

1466
01:27:43,820 --> 01:27:46,420
They do little else.

1467
01:27:51,860 --> 01:27:53,070
Oh...

1468
01:27:53,070 --> 01:27:56,500
Sorry, boys. I'm so changeable!

1469
01:27:56,500 --> 01:27:59,260
It is a weakness with me, but to be fair to myself,

1470
01:27:59,260 --> 01:28:01,060
it is my only weakness.

1471
01:28:01,060 --> 01:28:02,900
You can't be allowed to continue.

1472
01:28:04,900 --> 01:28:06,500
You just can't.

1473
01:28:06,500 --> 01:28:09,060
I would try to convince you,

1474
01:28:09,060 --> 01:28:12,940
but everything I have to say has already crossed your mind.

1475
01:28:17,860 --> 01:28:20,180
Probably my answer has crossed yours.

1476
01:28:45,700 --> 01:28:57,200

